1
00:02:58,387 --> 00:03:01,473
Right into the car.
To the back of the car.

2
00:03:01,515 --> 00:03:04,476
Watch your step.
Step lively, please.

3
00:03:04,518 --> 00:03:06,812
That's all.
Take the next train.

4
00:03:10,691 --> 00:03:12,067
Step back.

5
00:04:32,105 --> 00:04:34,233
-Look here, Doris--
-Shut up!

6
00:04:34,316 --> 00:04:36,276
My dear husband!

7
00:04:37,986 --> 00:04:40,405
Oh, no. Doris, please!

8
00:04:41,865 --> 00:04:43,158
Don't, Doris!

9
00:04:47,079 --> 00:04:48,247
Oh, Doris!

10
00:04:56,797 --> 00:04:58,257
Help! Help!

11
00:04:58,340 --> 00:04:59,967
Help! Murder!

12
00:05:01,093 --> 00:05:03,387
Help! Help!

13
00:05:15,691 --> 00:05:17,150
No!

14
00:05:18,026 --> 00:05:20,988
No more, please.

15
00:05:59,693 --> 00:06:01,111
7:30

16
00:06:11,747 --> 00:06:13,415
7:30

17
00:06:19,588 --> 00:06:21,924
You said it. 7:30.

18
00:07:08,011 --> 00:07:09,346
Hello, Pinky.

19
00:07:20,148 --> 00:07:21,483
Hello, Pinkie.

20
00:07:24,027 --> 00:07:25,571
You feel all right?

21
00:07:25,654 --> 00:07:28,365
No. Why?

22
00:07:28,448 --> 00:07:31,159
You were making some funny noises
in the night.

23
00:07:31,243 --> 00:07:32,911
I always do, don't l?

24
00:07:32,995 --> 00:07:36,123
That is, you always say
that I always do. How do I know?

25
00:07:36,206 --> 00:07:38,458
You always do,
but not this kind.

26
00:07:38,542 --> 00:07:40,002
What kind?

27
00:07:40,085 --> 00:07:43,338
I don't remember exactly,
but sort of like--

28
00:07:49,303 --> 00:07:52,055
-Like that, sort of.
-Really? You don't say.

29
00:07:52,139 --> 00:07:53,557
Yeah.

30
00:07:53,640 --> 00:07:55,559
-Fascinating.
-Huh?

31
00:07:55,642 --> 00:07:57,769
I say I sound fascinating.

32
00:07:57,853 --> 00:07:59,855
You'll do--

33
00:08:02,983 --> 00:08:05,527
-Hot dog!
-What?

34
00:08:05,611 --> 00:08:07,529
Wait a second.

35
00:08:07,613 --> 00:08:09,156
What is it?

36
00:08:09,239 --> 00:08:10,657
Woman shot her husband.

37
00:08:10,741 --> 00:08:12,284
Kill him?

38
00:08:13,577 --> 00:08:16,121
Wait a second.
I think she, uh--

39
00:08:17,122 --> 00:08:18,373
Let's see.

40
00:08:20,209 --> 00:08:22,753
-Nope.
-That's a shame.

41
00:08:22,836 --> 00:08:24,755
Condition critical, though.

42
00:08:24,838 --> 00:08:26,298
Congratulations.

43
00:08:26,381 --> 00:08:27,716
Wow!

44
00:08:28,675 --> 00:08:29,927
What?

45
00:08:30,010 --> 00:08:31,762
-Wait a second.
-What is it?

46
00:08:31,845 --> 00:08:34,348
-Find it in yours.
-lt isn't in here.

47
00:08:34,431 --> 00:08:38,227
He was playing her fast and loose,
so she caught him out and shot him.

48
00:08:38,310 --> 00:08:39,686
Who?

49
00:08:39,770 --> 00:08:42,773
-This lady l've been telling you about.
-Some lady.

50
00:08:45,234 --> 00:08:47,319
Serves him right,
the little two-timer.

51
00:08:47,402 --> 00:08:50,280
Says here he's 5'11, weighs 180.
Some little.

52
00:08:50,364 --> 00:08:53,492
Little in spirit,
I mean, of course.

53
00:08:53,575 --> 00:08:57,162
I don't approve of people rushing
around carrying loaded revolvers.

54
00:08:57,246 --> 00:08:59,498
Depends on who they're rushing at.

55
00:08:59,581 --> 00:09:03,335
Is that what they taught you
at Yale Law School?

56
00:09:03,377 --> 00:09:04,711
It's not funny.

57
00:09:04,795 --> 00:09:07,422
Contempt for the law
is the first thing--

58
00:09:07,506 --> 00:09:08,924
Come in.

59
00:09:10,342 --> 00:09:13,262
Better get movin', you two.
Heavy traffic today.

60
00:09:22,145 --> 00:09:23,522
Attagirl!

61
00:09:25,482 --> 00:09:27,025
You big pig.

62
00:09:27,067 --> 00:09:29,027
-Let him go by.
-He wants the whole road.

63
00:09:29,069 --> 00:09:32,197
All l'm saying is there are lots
of things that a man can do...

64
00:09:32,281 --> 00:09:34,783
and in society's eyes
it's all hunky-dory.

65
00:09:34,867 --> 00:09:38,996
A woman does the same thing,
and she's an outcast.

66
00:09:39,079 --> 00:09:40,664
-Finished?
-No.

67
00:09:40,747 --> 00:09:43,166
I'm not blaming you personally,
Adam, because this is so.

68
00:09:43,250 --> 00:09:46,587
-That's awfully large of you.
-No, it's not your fault.

69
00:09:46,670 --> 00:09:50,215
Why let this deplorable system
seep into our courts of law...

70
00:09:50,299 --> 00:09:52,843
where women
are supposed to be equal?

71
00:09:52,926 --> 00:09:55,387
Mostly, I think,
females get advantages.

72
00:09:55,429 --> 00:09:58,056
We don't want advantages,
and we don't want prejudices.

73
00:09:58,140 --> 00:10:01,685
Don't get excited, honey.
You're giving me the Bryn Mawr accent.

74
00:10:01,768 --> 00:10:04,855
What did she try to do?
She tried to keep her home intact.

75
00:10:04,938 --> 00:10:06,982
By knocking off her husband.

76
00:10:07,065 --> 00:10:09,526
She didn't knock him off.
He's alive.

77
00:10:09,610 --> 00:10:12,029
-She tried. She missed.
-Now supposing--

78
00:10:12,112 --> 00:10:14,656
-You wanna give her another shot at him?
-No, I don't.

79
00:10:18,202 --> 00:10:20,120
-lt burns my goat.
-Your what?

80
00:10:20,204 --> 00:10:21,663
My goat!

81
00:10:21,747 --> 00:10:23,665
Crime should be punished,
not condoned.

82
00:10:23,749 --> 00:10:26,168
-lf a woman commits it.
-Anybody. Pull over.

83
00:10:36,053 --> 00:10:37,971
-Sorry.
-Aw, you lady drivers!

84
00:10:38,055 --> 00:10:40,140
You'll put me away yet!

85
00:10:50,567 --> 00:10:52,110
-Morning, sir.
-Morning.

86
00:10:52,194 --> 00:10:54,154
-Morning, Roy.
-They down?

87
00:10:54,238 --> 00:10:57,950
Just now. We've got five assaults and
seven robberies, and l'm still counting.

88
00:10:57,991 --> 00:10:59,993
-You're still young.
-Not for long.

89
00:11:00,035 --> 00:11:01,995
Mommy's only got
one pair of brains.

90
00:11:02,037 --> 00:11:03,997
I may give up smoking,
you know that?

91
00:11:04,039 --> 00:11:05,999
What's this habeas corpus on 904A?

92
00:11:06,083 --> 00:11:08,001
-Search me.
-No sense to it.

93
00:11:08,085 --> 00:11:10,254
Why should I give up smoking
if I like it?

94
00:11:10,337 --> 00:11:12,631
-Oh, no.
-Something?

95
00:11:12,673 --> 00:11:14,758
-Good heavens.
-What?

96
00:11:16,343 --> 00:11:19,263
The one case I don't want
is the case I get.

97
00:11:19,346 --> 00:11:21,306
That's always the way.
Rule of the profession.

98
00:11:21,390 --> 00:11:23,350
-But this.
-Which one?

99
00:11:23,392 --> 00:11:26,186
This hysterical Hannah
who tried to kill her husband.

100
00:11:26,270 --> 00:11:28,355
-My wife feels--
-That's a cinch.

101
00:11:28,438 --> 00:11:30,357
You've already got
your full confession.

102
00:11:30,440 --> 00:11:32,359
That's the kind of case
you take your knitting. A cinch.

103
00:11:32,442 --> 00:11:34,194
-A cinch?
-What?

104
00:11:34,278 --> 00:11:37,698
-You're not married to my wife.
-How do you know?

105
00:11:37,739 --> 00:11:40,075
A cinch. I think I oughta
poke you one, Roy.

106
00:11:41,743 --> 00:11:43,704
-Yes, sir.
-Adam, you got a minute?

107
00:11:43,745 --> 00:11:45,205
Right now, chief.

108
00:11:53,130 --> 00:11:54,381
Cinch.

109
00:11:56,258 --> 00:11:59,011
A case of overwrought.
Simple overwrought.

110
00:11:59,094 --> 00:12:02,055
I've noticed guys doing
that sort of thing more and more.

111
00:12:02,097 --> 00:12:04,349
I've got a theory.
You wanna hear it?

112
00:12:04,433 --> 00:12:06,894
I think the human race
is having a nervous breakdown.

113
00:12:11,857 --> 00:12:14,109
Which is why I am compelled...

114
00:12:14,193 --> 00:12:18,572
to return same to you
for further revision.

115
00:12:18,655 --> 00:12:21,491
If this course seems to you...

116
00:12:21,575 --> 00:12:23,869
unnecessarily exacting...

117
00:12:23,911 --> 00:12:27,414
may I again remind you
that unless we obtain...

118
00:12:27,497 --> 00:12:30,626
certiorari
in the immediate future--

119
00:12:30,709 --> 00:12:32,461
-Grace.
-Yeah?

120
00:12:32,544 --> 00:12:35,464
What do you think of a man
who's unfaithful to his wife?

121
00:12:35,547 --> 00:12:36,924
Not nice, but--

122
00:12:37,007 --> 00:12:40,552
What about a woman who's
unfaithful to her husband?

123
00:12:40,594 --> 00:12:42,596
-Something terrible.
-Aha!

124
00:12:42,679 --> 00:12:44,932
-What?
-Why the difference?

125
00:12:45,015 --> 00:12:48,644
Why not nice if he does it,
and something terrible if she does it?

126
00:12:48,727 --> 00:12:51,522
-l don't make the rules.
-Sure you do. We all do.

127
00:12:52,940 --> 00:12:55,442
Unless we obtain certiorari
in the immediate future--

128
00:12:55,526 --> 00:12:59,279
The matter looks hopeless.

129
00:12:59,363 --> 00:13:02,616
I again urge you to study
and consider United Zinc--

130
00:13:03,825 --> 00:13:06,703
A boy sows a wild oat or two,
the world winks.

131
00:13:06,787 --> 00:13:09,748
A girl does the same, scandal.

132
00:13:09,831 --> 00:13:11,875
-Yeah.
-Hello, honey.

133
00:13:11,959 --> 00:13:14,503
Hello.
Hello, husband.

134
00:13:14,586 --> 00:13:17,256
-You've been on my mind.
-Where you been keeping yourself?

135
00:13:17,339 --> 00:13:19,716
-l've been resting up after a hard--
-Adam!

136
00:13:19,800 --> 00:13:22,511
You know the woman who shot her
husband yesterday? Want a good laugh?

137
00:13:22,594 --> 00:13:24,763
-Sure, go ahead.
-Well, l'm elected.

138
00:13:24,805 --> 00:13:27,808
I was gonna ask the chief to let me off
to keep peace at home.

139
00:13:27,850 --> 00:13:32,813
-What?
-The boss wants a quick conviction...

140
00:13:32,855 --> 00:13:35,649
and l'm the guy
who can get it for him.

141
00:13:35,732 --> 00:13:38,318
-So he says.
-You big he-men make me sick!

142
00:13:38,402 --> 00:13:41,280
-What?
-An outrage, that's what I think.

143
00:13:41,321 --> 00:13:43,782
You're getting awful dramatic.

144
00:13:43,824 --> 00:13:45,951
Why? What's so funny?

145
00:13:47,870 --> 00:13:50,956
Nothing. You just sound cute
when you get causey.

146
00:13:53,041 --> 00:13:55,252
Hello? Hello?

147
00:14:09,683 --> 00:14:12,686
Did you ever hear about the straw
that broke the camel's back?

148
00:14:12,769 --> 00:14:14,188
Many times.

149
00:14:14,229 --> 00:14:16,690
Well, itjust happened again,
right on that phone.

150
00:14:18,358 --> 00:14:21,737
The last straw
on a female camel.

151
00:14:21,820 --> 00:14:24,489
-Right on that phone?
-Yeah. Take all this down.

152
00:14:24,573 --> 00:14:26,033
This is important.

153
00:14:26,074 --> 00:14:28,452
There's a woman named--
Wait a minute.

154
00:14:28,535 --> 00:14:31,997
Hey, Bobby, bring me the morning papers
in here right away, will you, please?

155
00:14:32,080 --> 00:14:34,208
Whatever her name was,
she shot her husband last night.

156
00:14:34,291 --> 00:14:36,835
-Served him right.
-l'm not talking. This is big.

157
00:14:36,877 --> 00:14:38,462
One: Find out where she is.

158
00:14:38,545 --> 00:14:42,883
Two: Get me copies of all the police
and court records that are available.

159
00:14:42,966 --> 00:14:45,636
Three: Find out who's handling her.
Probably Legal Aid Society.

160
00:14:45,719 --> 00:14:47,638
If that's it, let me talk
to Rogers down there.

161
00:14:47,721 --> 00:14:50,057
If she's privately defended,
find out who, let me talk to them.

162
00:14:50,140 --> 00:14:53,018
Four: Get Miss Bassett
at Women's Council for Equal Rights.

163
00:14:53,060 --> 00:14:56,188
Five: Get my husband on the phone.
Six: Don't get my husband.

164
00:14:56,271 --> 00:14:58,774
-Thank you, Bobby.
-Woman popped her ever-lovin'.

165
00:14:58,857 --> 00:15:01,318
Yeah. Thanks. Beat it.
Attinger.

166
00:15:01,401 --> 00:15:02,945
A-T-T-l-N-G-E-R.

167
00:15:03,028 --> 00:15:06,198
Yes, Doris Attinger. I want
to see her today without fail.

168
00:15:06,281 --> 00:15:08,742
-What's going to happen?
-Plenty.

169
00:15:08,784 --> 00:15:11,662
What explanation have you got?

170
00:15:11,745 --> 00:15:14,915
She's crazy, that's all.
That's the only explanation.

171
00:15:14,998 --> 00:15:16,583
Plain crazy.

172
00:15:16,667 --> 00:15:18,377
Plain crazy.

173
00:15:18,418 --> 00:15:20,921
She's always been crazy,
if you want a fact.

174
00:15:22,297 --> 00:15:25,634
-Crazy when you married her?
-Certainly. A fruitcake.

175
00:15:27,719 --> 00:15:30,889
-Why did you marry her?
-How should I know? Who knows?

176
00:15:30,931 --> 00:15:33,600
Why'd you marry yours?
Does anybody know?

177
00:15:33,684 --> 00:15:38,397
Wait, Mr. Attinger. Let's not play
around with this too free and easy.

178
00:15:38,480 --> 00:15:39,940
After you've filed complaint--

179
00:15:40,023 --> 00:15:42,860
I've been complaining ever since
the day I got married to her.

180
00:15:42,943 --> 00:15:46,154
Go ahead and file it.
She's nuts! That's my complaint.

181
00:15:47,322 --> 00:15:49,449
I'd like to see her
put away somewheres.

182
00:15:49,533 --> 00:15:51,451
That's all. Out of my hair.

183
00:15:51,535 --> 00:15:54,788
Murderers running around.
What kind of a town is this?

184
00:15:54,872 --> 00:15:57,791
We don't have so many murderers
running around, Miss--

185
00:15:57,875 --> 00:16:00,586
but we have a lot of other things
just as bad.

186
00:16:00,627 --> 00:16:02,671
You mean like me, huh?

187
00:16:02,754 --> 00:16:05,674
Listen, bub, I connect with you.
You ain't over my head.

188
00:16:05,757 --> 00:16:09,219
-Good.
-l'm gettin' a lawyer on my own.

189
00:16:09,303 --> 00:16:11,680
-l gotta get her put away.
-Listen, pal.

190
00:16:11,763 --> 00:16:14,099
You're running
way ahead of yourself.

191
00:16:14,141 --> 00:16:17,311
You just give us the facts
and the background.

192
00:16:17,394 --> 00:16:19,813
We'll get a conviction
on an attempted murder...

193
00:16:19,897 --> 00:16:23,984
or first-degree assault or however else
the office wishes to proceed.

194
00:16:24,067 --> 00:16:25,485
You understand that?

195
00:16:27,905 --> 00:16:29,656
What do I do?

196
00:16:29,740 --> 00:16:33,285
You just tell us the truth as clearly
and as accurately as you can.

197
00:16:34,328 --> 00:16:36,330
Shoot. I mean, go ahead.

198
00:16:38,207 --> 00:16:40,042
State your full name.

199
00:16:40,125 --> 00:16:42,169
Warren Francis Attinger.

200
00:16:42,252 --> 00:16:43,587
Where do you live?

201
00:16:43,670 --> 00:16:45,297
66 West 12th Street.

202
00:16:45,339 --> 00:16:47,299
-New York City?
-New York City.

203
00:16:47,341 --> 00:16:48,467
Occupation?

204
00:16:48,509 --> 00:16:50,469
No occupation.

205
00:16:50,511 --> 00:16:53,514
-Housewife.
-That's right. Housewife.

206
00:16:53,597 --> 00:16:55,432
-All right.
-And mother?

207
00:16:55,516 --> 00:16:56,767
Yes.

208
00:16:58,685 --> 00:17:00,646
No, thank you.

209
00:17:00,687 --> 00:17:03,649
I don't believe women should smoke.
You'll excuse me saying it.

210
00:17:03,690 --> 00:17:05,651
Yes, l'll excuse you.

211
00:17:05,692 --> 00:17:07,694
-Now--
-lt's not feminine.

212
00:17:08,987 --> 00:17:11,907
How long have you been married,
Mrs. Attinger?

213
00:17:11,990 --> 00:17:14,034
Nine years and four months.

214
00:17:14,117 --> 00:17:16,286
-l see.
-And 12 days.

215
00:17:16,370 --> 00:17:18,622
-Finished?
-Yes, thank you.

216
00:17:18,705 --> 00:17:20,999
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

217
00:17:21,041 --> 00:17:23,043
And you have three children?

218
00:17:23,085 --> 00:17:25,796
Warren, Jr., he's eight...

219
00:17:25,879 --> 00:17:29,132
Allan, he's seven,
and Trudy, she's six.

220
00:17:29,216 --> 00:17:30,759
That's all.

221
00:17:30,843 --> 00:17:35,556
When did you begin to suspect that you
were losing your husband's affection?

222
00:17:38,475 --> 00:17:40,978
When he stopped battin' me around.

223
00:17:41,061 --> 00:17:44,439
-When was that?
-Eleven months ago. March 14.

224
00:17:45,440 --> 00:17:46,942
He struck you?

225
00:17:47,025 --> 00:17:49,611
First time, he broke a tooth.

226
00:17:49,695 --> 00:17:51,655
-My tooth.
-l see.

227
00:17:51,738 --> 00:17:53,782
Upper left molar.

228
00:17:53,866 --> 00:17:57,035
-And how often--
-lt's capped now. You can't notice it.

229
00:17:58,370 --> 00:18:01,707
Good. Now, let's start
with the day of the accident--

230
00:18:01,790 --> 00:18:05,627
Oh, no accident.
I wanted to shoot him.

231
00:18:05,711 --> 00:18:08,672
Suppose we decide later
just what you wanted to do.

232
00:18:09,506 --> 00:18:11,091
Silly.

233
00:18:11,175 --> 00:18:13,969
The difference between ten years
in prison and freedom...

234
00:18:14,052 --> 00:18:16,013
is not silly, Mrs. Attinger.

235
00:18:16,096 --> 00:18:17,472
Call me Doris.

236
00:18:17,556 --> 00:18:19,516
Pay attention to what l'm saying.

237
00:18:19,600 --> 00:18:21,894
I don't care what happens to me.

238
00:18:21,935 --> 00:18:25,063
Do you care what happens
to Warren and Allan and Trudy?

239
00:18:25,147 --> 00:18:27,608
Yes, I do.
I wanna go home.

240
00:18:27,691 --> 00:18:29,651
Can't you fix it
so I should go home?

241
00:18:29,735 --> 00:18:32,863
Not right now,
but we're working on it. Here.

242
00:18:32,946 --> 00:18:35,908
I promised my kids l'd take 'em
to Coney lsland tomorrow.

243
00:18:35,991 --> 00:18:37,576
Yes, you drink that.

244
00:18:37,659 --> 00:18:42,122
Now, you would help us very much
if you could reconstruct the day.

245
00:18:42,956 --> 00:18:44,458
All of yesterday.

246
00:18:47,669 --> 00:18:50,631
Well, first thing in the morning...

247
00:18:51,924 --> 00:18:54,259
-Yes?
-l woke up.

248
00:18:54,301 --> 00:18:56,887
-Yes?
-And I see he didn't sleep home.

249
00:18:57,804 --> 00:18:59,848
You were shocked and surprised.

250
00:18:59,932 --> 00:19:02,184
Oh, no. Not shocked,
not surprised.

251
00:19:02,267 --> 00:19:04,770
He used to not do that a lot--
come home.

252
00:19:05,854 --> 00:19:07,856
Did you ever question him
about his behavior?

253
00:19:07,940 --> 00:19:09,191
Certainly.

254
00:19:09,274 --> 00:19:11,735
-Did he offer any explanation?
-Certainly.

255
00:19:11,818 --> 00:19:14,071
He told me to shut up
and mind my own business.

256
00:19:15,322 --> 00:19:16,615
I see.

257
00:19:16,657 --> 00:19:19,076
But yesterday, I got worried.

258
00:19:20,536 --> 00:19:22,913
Not worried, mad.

259
00:19:22,996 --> 00:19:25,791
-l got mad. You know why?
-Why?

260
00:19:25,874 --> 00:19:28,001
'Cause it was the fourth night
in a row he didn't.

261
00:19:29,837 --> 00:19:31,588
-Come home?
-Yeah.

262
00:19:31,672 --> 00:19:34,967
-And that made you angry?
-Sure. lt was gettin' a habit with him.

263
00:19:35,050 --> 00:19:38,387
So I sent the kids to school,
and I went and bought a gun.

264
00:19:38,470 --> 00:19:41,390
-Where?
-This hock shop I go to.

265
00:19:41,473 --> 00:19:45,435
I bought a gun and they gave me
a book how to--free.

266
00:19:45,519 --> 00:19:49,314
Had you decided by this time
exactly what you planned to do?

267
00:19:51,525 --> 00:19:55,320
I'll tell you the honest truth.
I didn't decide nothin'.

268
00:19:55,404 --> 00:19:58,115
I was doin' everything
like in a dream--

269
00:19:58,198 --> 00:20:02,035
like I was watchin' myself,
but I couldn't help it.

270
00:20:02,119 --> 00:20:04,246
-Like a dream?
-Yeah. Wait a second.

271
00:20:04,329 --> 00:20:05,706
You got all that?

272
00:20:05,789 --> 00:20:09,334
Like I was watching myself
but couldn't help it. Like a dream.

273
00:20:09,376 --> 00:20:11,378
Yeah, that's good.
Now, go on, Doris.

274
00:20:12,462 --> 00:20:16,425
So then I got very hungry.

275
00:20:16,508 --> 00:20:18,594
-When?
-When I bought the gun.

276
00:20:18,677 --> 00:20:21,054
-Yeah?
-So I went in this hamburger place...

277
00:20:21,138 --> 00:20:25,058
and I ate two--rare--
and one lemon meringue pie.

278
00:20:26,894 --> 00:20:28,312
And then?

279
00:20:29,146 --> 00:20:31,398
Then I was still hungry.

280
00:20:31,481 --> 00:20:32,900
Think of that.

281
00:20:36,361 --> 00:20:39,740
So I walked all around...

282
00:20:39,823 --> 00:20:42,993
and I kept talkin' to myself
not to be foolish.

283
00:20:43,076 --> 00:20:45,746
-And then?
-And then I called up Warren.

284
00:20:45,829 --> 00:20:48,498
He was just gettin'
his lunch hour by now.

285
00:20:48,582 --> 00:20:52,961
I said to him I wanna see him important,
so if we could have lunch together.

286
00:20:53,045 --> 00:20:55,422
So he said no, naturally.

287
00:20:55,506 --> 00:20:58,091
So I asked him,
You comin' home after?

288
00:20:58,175 --> 00:21:00,260
So he says, What for?

289
00:21:00,344 --> 00:21:04,097
So I said to him,
Don't you live there no more?

290
00:21:04,181 --> 00:21:08,519
So he says, Don't bother me at the
office. You want me to lose my job?

291
00:21:08,602 --> 00:21:10,812
Loud. So then he hung up.

292
00:21:12,064 --> 00:21:13,774
And what did you do?

293
00:21:13,857 --> 00:21:15,817
I had a cup of coffee.

294
00:21:16,735 --> 00:21:17,819
Where?

295
00:21:17,903 --> 00:21:20,030
The same place as him,
only he didn't see me.

296
00:21:20,113 --> 00:21:22,616
It was crowded.
The Buffet Exchange.

297
00:21:23,825 --> 00:21:26,203
So then I bought
some chocolate nut bars...

298
00:21:26,286 --> 00:21:29,915
and I went outside of his office
and I waited the whole afternoon.

299
00:21:29,957 --> 00:21:34,545
And I kept eatin' the candy bars
and waitin' until he come out.

300
00:21:34,628 --> 00:21:37,005
And then I followed him.

301
00:21:37,089 --> 00:21:39,007
And then I shot him.

302
00:21:43,136 --> 00:21:46,431
And after you shot him,
how did you feel then?

303
00:21:51,228 --> 00:21:52,521
Hungry.

304
00:22:07,160 --> 00:22:09,121
Everything looks lovely, Mary.

305
00:22:10,163 --> 00:22:13,625
-You must be dead.
-l don't care, except the extra help.

306
00:22:13,709 --> 00:22:16,003
With me, the more help I got,
the harder I have to work.

307
00:22:16,086 --> 00:22:18,422
-l'm not late, am l?
-lsn't that typical?

308
00:22:18,505 --> 00:22:19,923
Twenty minutes of 8:00.

309
00:22:21,675 --> 00:22:24,261
Oh! Beautiful!

310
00:22:25,470 --> 00:22:27,222
Uh, I don't--

311
00:22:34,521 --> 00:22:36,481
Can you get dressed
in four minutes?

312
00:22:37,900 --> 00:22:40,861
Of course I can't get dressed
in four minutes.

313
00:22:40,903 --> 00:22:43,655
Why, sure, darling,
I can get dressed in four minutes.

314
00:22:43,697 --> 00:22:47,034
I may have a little trouble
getting in a bath in that time.

315
00:23:03,300 --> 00:23:05,969
You are hurrying up,
aren't you, darling?

316
00:23:06,053 --> 00:23:09,431
Do you remember
Judge Marcasson's wife's name?

317
00:23:09,515 --> 00:23:12,601
Oh, I do. Alice.

318
00:23:12,684 --> 00:23:15,771
I hope Kip knows enough to behave
with the judges around.

319
00:23:15,854 --> 00:23:18,607
I'll keep him playing the piano
as much as possible.

320
00:23:19,525 --> 00:23:21,860
-Have a good day?
-Yeah.

321
00:23:23,612 --> 00:23:25,572
-You make a lot of money?
-No.

322
00:23:27,032 --> 00:23:30,953
-Better than money.
-Really? What?

323
00:23:31,036 --> 00:23:33,539
A very interesting development.

324
00:23:34,456 --> 00:23:35,916
Very.

325
00:23:35,958 --> 00:23:37,292
Good.

326
00:23:37,376 --> 00:23:40,337
I hope you'll think so
when you find out what it is.

327
00:23:40,420 --> 00:23:43,006
It may jar you
a bit at first, but--

328
00:23:49,346 --> 00:23:50,597
Pinky!

329
00:23:51,390 --> 00:23:52,975
Calling me?

330
00:23:54,351 --> 00:23:55,602
What's that?

331
00:23:55,686 --> 00:23:57,646
Just the best hat in the world.

332
00:23:58,730 --> 00:24:00,691
For the best head.

333
00:24:00,774 --> 00:24:04,611
I may ask you to come home late
every single night.

334
00:24:10,075 --> 00:24:14,162
Someday they're gonna build
a statue to you somewhere.

335
00:24:15,455 --> 00:24:18,083
I said--
Now, what about that?

336
00:24:18,125 --> 00:24:20,377
-That's sweet.
-lsn't that absolutely a miracle?

337
00:24:20,460 --> 00:24:22,838
You look kind of like Grandma Moses.

338
00:24:22,921 --> 00:24:25,299
-Yeah?
-Your mother and father are here.

339
00:24:25,382 --> 00:24:28,427
-Tell 'em we'll be right down.
-Tell 'em to fix themselves a drink!

340
00:24:28,468 --> 00:24:30,137
-What?
-A drink.

341
00:24:30,220 --> 00:24:31,471
No, thanks.

342
00:24:32,389 --> 00:24:33,932
What?

343
00:24:34,016 --> 00:24:35,976
I said I don't want one, thanks.

344
00:24:36,894 --> 00:24:38,478
For the love of heaven.

345
00:24:38,562 --> 00:24:39,813
How do I look?

346
00:24:39,897 --> 00:24:42,482
Oh, boy, you look handsome.

347
00:24:42,566 --> 00:24:46,778
-This is a dress I have on.
-Oh, it's beautiful!

348
00:24:47,738 --> 00:24:49,656
They'll be right down, Mrs. Bonner.

349
00:24:49,740 --> 00:24:51,700
-How are you, Mary?
-Hello, everybody.

350
00:24:51,783 --> 00:24:54,036
-Hello, honey.
-lt's just us.

351
00:24:54,119 --> 00:24:56,580
-Good evening, ladies and gentlemen.
-Well, son, how are you?

352
00:24:56,663 --> 00:24:58,040
Dad. Hi.

353
00:24:58,123 --> 00:25:00,083
-Hello, Adam.
-Hello, dear.

354
00:25:00,167 --> 00:25:03,587
Adam, mix the drinks. l'm sorry
we're so late, but l'm not to blame.

355
00:25:03,670 --> 00:25:06,673
-l have an irresponsible husband.
-Hereditary.

356
00:25:06,757 --> 00:25:09,510
We're gonna have
the most sensational dinner.

357
00:25:09,593 --> 00:25:13,180
-Oh, my dress. Do it up, will you?
-l'm sorry. I forgot my glasses.

358
00:25:13,263 --> 00:25:16,850
You did? Adam!
Come in here and fasten me up.

359
00:25:16,934 --> 00:25:19,353
-Sit down.
-Fasten? Oh, here, Pop.

360
00:25:19,436 --> 00:25:21,188
Mix 'em, don't drink 'em.

361
00:25:21,271 --> 00:25:23,232
I suppose someday somebody
will invent something--

362
00:25:23,315 --> 00:25:24,858
You've got no complaint.

363
00:25:24,942 --> 00:25:27,986
You oughta see some of the things
that I used to have to handle.

364
00:25:28,028 --> 00:25:29,821
Hooks and eyes.

365
00:25:29,863 --> 00:25:32,449
She had an evening gown one time
had about two thousand.

366
00:25:32,533 --> 00:25:35,786
-Don't exaggerate.
-All right, then. One thousand.

367
00:25:35,869 --> 00:25:38,455
Used to start to hook her up
right after breakfast.

368
00:25:38,539 --> 00:25:40,499
-Good evening.
-Good evening, Mary.

369
00:25:40,582 --> 00:25:43,043
Anybody else important here yet?

370
00:25:43,085 --> 00:25:46,380
Well, look at us. All the way
from across the hall and on time.

371
00:25:46,463 --> 00:25:48,382
-Don't we look nice?
-You certainly do.

372
00:25:48,465 --> 00:25:51,176
-You know Emerald Messel, don't you?
-Emerald, how are you?

373
00:25:51,260 --> 00:25:54,304
You know Adam's father and mother?
Emerald Messel.

374
00:25:54,388 --> 00:25:57,516
She's just been proposing to me.
That's why we're on time.

375
00:25:57,558 --> 00:25:58,851
Ha, ha!

376
00:25:58,892 --> 00:26:00,853
No humor, but stinkin' rich.

377
00:26:02,646 --> 00:26:04,690
-What do you want to drink?
-Whatever's going.

378
00:26:04,773 --> 00:26:06,775
-Dad, would you be an angel?
-You bet.

379
00:26:06,859 --> 00:26:08,944
-Need some help, old friend?
-No, thanks.

380
00:26:09,027 --> 00:26:12,072
Why not? She may be your wife,
but she's my lawyer.

381
00:26:12,155 --> 00:26:16,285
Amanda, my love, why do you stay
married to a legal beagle with ten thumbs?

382
00:26:16,368 --> 00:26:18,495
All right, Kip.
That's enough.

383
00:26:18,579 --> 00:26:20,330
Not for me it's not.

384
00:26:20,414 --> 00:26:22,374
-Why don't you go play the piano?
-All right.

385
00:26:22,457 --> 00:26:25,252
-l suppose that is why I was invited.
-That's right.

386
00:26:25,335 --> 00:26:29,882
Somebody ought to bring me a drink.
I choose Amanda.

387
00:26:35,429 --> 00:26:38,348
Are you the judges?
Somebody said judges were coming.

388
00:26:40,142 --> 00:26:41,935
Hello, Dotty.

389
00:26:42,019 --> 00:26:45,480
You always have judges here.
Why is that? To get in good with them?

390
00:26:49,443 --> 00:26:52,029
How very nice to see you,
Mrs. Marcasson.

391
00:26:52,779 --> 00:26:55,532
How very nice to see you
Mrs. Marcasson

392
00:26:55,616 --> 00:26:58,619
How very nice to see you
Mrs. Marcasson

393
00:26:58,702 --> 00:27:02,831
The judge is standing by
but I really don't know why

394
00:27:04,750 --> 00:27:08,170
What were you doing
down in my bailiwick today?

395
00:27:08,253 --> 00:27:10,672
Oh, just a little ambulance chasing.

396
00:27:10,756 --> 00:27:12,799
-Successful?
-Well, I got the case.

397
00:27:12,883 --> 00:27:14,134
What case?

398
00:27:14,218 --> 00:27:17,304
A girl named Doris Attinger shot
her husband. l'm going to defend her.

399
00:27:21,808 --> 00:27:23,435
Dinner is served, madam.

400
00:27:24,811 --> 00:27:27,231
Oh, well, let's go on in, everyone.

401
00:27:30,067 --> 00:27:31,485
That's all right, darling.

402
00:27:36,949 --> 00:27:38,784
The trouble with this picture--
it drags.

403
00:27:38,867 --> 00:27:40,369
Shut up, Kip.

404
00:27:40,452 --> 00:27:43,330
Are you all sure
that you want to see this?

405
00:27:43,413 --> 00:27:44,665
I don't.

406
00:27:45,707 --> 00:27:47,209
Look at that.

407
00:27:48,335 --> 00:27:51,463
This is our main house.
The cottage is out here by the camera.

408
00:27:51,505 --> 00:27:54,007
I can't see it.

409
00:27:54,091 --> 00:27:57,261
What an unusual name.
Your idea, Adam?

410
00:28:06,019 --> 00:28:08,564
Cute outfit, Amanda.
Really cute.

411
00:28:12,192 --> 00:28:15,487
Mighty pretty country up there!

412
00:28:16,864 --> 00:28:18,740
Ha, ha.

413
00:28:18,824 --> 00:28:21,577
I know a lady collapsed a lung once
laughing like that.

414
00:28:54,818 --> 00:28:58,071
Oh, cute outfit, Adam!
Really cute!

415
00:29:09,374 --> 00:29:11,877
Look at those darling dogs.

416
00:29:11,960 --> 00:29:14,546
One, two, three.

417
00:29:14,630 --> 00:29:16,715
Sort of an animal picture,
isn't it?

418
00:29:18,592 --> 00:29:21,553
I would say this movie
has a rather limited appeal.

419
00:29:21,637 --> 00:29:23,972
-What's that anyhow?
-lt's the mortgage.

420
00:29:24,056 --> 00:29:26,225
That was the day
they paid off the mortgage.

421
00:29:26,266 --> 00:29:27,768
Brought it out myself.

422
00:29:29,353 --> 00:29:31,396
Looks like rubber from here.

423
00:29:33,190 --> 00:29:37,402
We acted this all out later, of course.
I mean, it's not actual.

424
00:29:37,444 --> 00:29:40,531
-All right, bigmouth, settle down.
-Oh, Kip!

425
00:29:49,706 --> 00:29:52,668
Seems much slower than
the other eight times l've seen it.

426
00:29:53,752 --> 00:29:55,754
Who took these pictures,
your cow?

427
00:29:58,674 --> 00:30:02,052
-You oughta be on the stage, Judge.
-Anywhere but in this picture.

428
00:30:04,137 --> 00:30:07,975
You should have taken a picture
of burning the mortgage.

429
00:30:08,058 --> 00:30:10,686
We did, Dad. Wait, look.

430
00:30:10,769 --> 00:30:14,731
Oh, cute, Adam. Very cute.

431
00:30:17,401 --> 00:30:19,736
Oh, expensive hot dogs.

432
00:30:23,073 --> 00:30:24,992
Our tree.

433
00:30:25,075 --> 00:30:28,203
Tree kissing, a famous
old Connecticut custom.

434
00:30:33,166 --> 00:30:36,920
Barn kissing, a famous
old Connecticut custom.

435
00:30:41,675 --> 00:30:43,218
What a funny--

436
00:31:06,408 --> 00:31:10,537
Wife kissing, a famous
old Connecticut custom.

437
00:31:13,207 --> 00:31:15,375
Okay, everybody, on your heads.

438
00:31:21,965 --> 00:31:25,177
As the sanking soo
sunks into the sinking sand...

439
00:31:25,219 --> 00:31:26,720
we say good-bye...

440
00:31:26,803 --> 00:31:29,890
to Bonner Hill
and the sickening home movies.

441
00:31:31,725 --> 00:31:33,936
All right! All right!

442
00:31:34,019 --> 00:31:35,979
You've said the same thing
nine times!

443
00:31:36,063 --> 00:31:39,441
For the tenth time then, will you
stay out of this Attinger thing?

444
00:31:39,525 --> 00:31:42,402
Did you have to sulk all evening,
and with a growl on your face?

445
00:31:42,486 --> 00:31:44,404
How could a man have
a growl on his face?

446
00:31:44,488 --> 00:31:47,157
If you think you're gonna turn a court
of law into a Punch-and-Judy show--

447
00:31:47,241 --> 00:31:51,119
Darling, please!
This means a great deal to me...

448
00:31:51,203 --> 00:31:52,788
and it's not a stunt.

449
00:31:52,871 --> 00:31:55,999
This poor woman. lsn't she
entitled to the same justice...

450
00:31:56,083 --> 00:31:58,210
that's usually reserved for men?

451
00:31:58,252 --> 00:32:00,254
The same unwritten law
that got Lennahan off.

452
00:32:00,337 --> 00:32:02,548
-Would you please--
-l know what you're going to say.

453
00:32:02,631 --> 00:32:04,800
He should have been convicted too,
but he wasn't.

454
00:32:04,883 --> 00:32:07,177
-Couldn't I please get one, little--
-You're not putting her away...

455
00:32:07,261 --> 00:32:09,429
because she had the misfortune
to be born a female.

456
00:32:09,513 --> 00:32:11,431
Just one word in edgewise.

457
00:32:11,515 --> 00:32:14,643
Could I please
get a word in edgewise?

458
00:32:14,726 --> 00:32:16,895
-Go ahead.
-Not one sybbal--

459
00:32:16,979 --> 00:32:20,941
Not one syllable of what you
have been blabbering here tonight--

460
00:32:21,024 --> 00:32:23,277
You always do that
when you get excited.

461
00:32:27,447 --> 00:32:30,450
I am going to cut you
into 12 little pieces...

462
00:32:30,534 --> 00:32:33,745
and feed you to the jury,
so get prepared for it.

463
00:32:44,256 --> 00:32:45,674
Good night, Pinky.

464
00:32:47,384 --> 00:32:49,303
Oh, good night.

465
00:33:08,363 --> 00:33:09,781
We're here.

466
00:33:09,823 --> 00:33:12,868
Have you agreed on a date
for the People v. Riverton?

467
00:33:12,951 --> 00:33:14,369
Yes, Your Honor.

468
00:33:27,049 --> 00:33:30,302
The People v. Delwyn
has been assigned to part three.

469
00:33:30,385 --> 00:33:33,472
All witnesses in that case
will proceed to that part.

470
00:33:33,514 --> 00:33:34,806
That's part three.

471
00:34:00,457 --> 00:34:02,376
People against Attinger.

472
00:34:03,418 --> 00:34:05,379
You may proceed.

473
00:34:05,462 --> 00:34:08,382
Your Honor, I move the case of the
People of the State of New York...

474
00:34:08,465 --> 00:34:10,968
against Doris Szabo Attinger
to trial.

475
00:34:11,051 --> 00:34:13,220
-ls the defendant ready?
-Defendant is ready.

476
00:34:13,303 --> 00:34:15,556
Very well. You may proceed
to select ajury.

477
00:34:22,688 --> 00:34:23,939
Paul Hurlock.

478
00:34:26,733 --> 00:34:28,652
Take your coat with you, please.

479
00:34:37,619 --> 00:34:40,247
Place your left hand on the Bible.
Raise your right hand.

480
00:34:40,330 --> 00:34:42,749
You swear you will true answers
make to all questions...

481
00:34:42,833 --> 00:34:44,918
put to you upon the challenges
touching upon your competence...

482
00:34:45,002 --> 00:34:47,004
as a fair and impartial juror
in this proceeding...

483
00:34:47,087 --> 00:34:50,132
between the people of New York and
Doris Szabo Attinger, so help you God?

484
00:34:50,215 --> 00:34:51,592
-l do.
-Be seated.

485
00:34:51,675 --> 00:34:53,594
State your full name and address.

486
00:34:53,677 --> 00:34:57,639
Paul Hurlock, 1731 Boylston Avenue,
New York City.

487
00:35:04,062 --> 00:35:06,398
Mr. Hurlock,
what's your occupation?

488
00:35:06,440 --> 00:35:08,025
Infants headgear.

489
00:35:09,443 --> 00:35:12,905
Are you personally acquainted
with one Warren Attinger?

490
00:35:12,988 --> 00:35:15,199
-No.
-Doris Szabo Attinger?

491
00:35:15,282 --> 00:35:17,659
-No.
-Beryl Caighn?

492
00:35:19,244 --> 00:35:22,289
Do you think that you're able to render
ajust and honest verdict...

493
00:35:22,372 --> 00:35:26,710
in this case as deduced by the evidence
of the law as laid down by the court?

494
00:35:26,793 --> 00:35:28,462
-Sure.
-Yes?

495
00:35:28,545 --> 00:35:31,465
-Uh, yes.
-The juror is acceptable to the People.

496
00:35:34,885 --> 00:35:37,804
-Good morning, Mr. Hurlock.
-Good morning.

497
00:35:37,888 --> 00:35:40,098
Do you believe
in equal rights for women?

498
00:35:40,182 --> 00:35:42,267
-What?
-Objection.

499
00:35:43,477 --> 00:35:46,438
May it please the court, I submit that
my entire line of defense...

500
00:35:46,480 --> 00:35:49,900
is based on the proposition
that persons of the female sex...

501
00:35:49,983 --> 00:35:53,862
should be dealt with before the law
as equals of persons of the male sex.

502
00:35:53,946 --> 00:35:57,324
I submit that I cannot
hope to argue this line...

503
00:35:57,407 --> 00:36:01,995
before minds hostile to
and prejudiced against the female sex.

504
00:36:03,121 --> 00:36:05,040
Objection still stands,
Your Honor.

505
00:36:05,123 --> 00:36:06,750
-Overruled.
-Exception.

506
00:36:07,835 --> 00:36:09,127
Repeat the question, Counselor.

507
00:36:09,211 --> 00:36:11,672
Do you believe
in equal rights for women?

508
00:36:11,713 --> 00:36:14,132
I should say not.

509
00:36:14,216 --> 00:36:17,052
The defendant challenges
this juror for cause.

510
00:36:17,845 --> 00:36:19,680
Excused.

511
00:36:19,763 --> 00:36:21,181
Benjamin Klausner.

512
00:36:32,651 --> 00:36:34,778
Your Honor, in view of the fact
that counsel have agreed...

513
00:36:34,862 --> 00:36:37,197
that alternate jurors
are not to be selected...

514
00:36:37,281 --> 00:36:41,159
may we proceed without making a call
for additional prospective jurors?

515
00:36:41,201 --> 00:36:42,494
You may proceed.

516
00:36:42,578 --> 00:36:45,789
Left hand on the Bible,
raise your right hand.

517
00:36:45,873 --> 00:36:48,792
You swear that you will true answers
make to all questions put to you...

518
00:36:48,876 --> 00:36:50,961
upon the challenges
touching upon your competence...

519
00:36:51,044 --> 00:36:52,963
as a fair and impartial juror
in this proceeding...

520
00:36:53,046 --> 00:36:55,716
between the people of New York and
Doris Szabo Attinger, so help you God?

521
00:36:55,799 --> 00:36:57,926
-l do.
-Be seated.

522
00:36:58,010 --> 00:37:00,053
-You're Benjamin Klows-ner?
-Klausner.

523
00:37:00,137 --> 00:37:03,599
-State your address.
-107 East 77th Street, New York City.

524
00:37:03,682 --> 00:37:06,727
-Occupation.
-Motion picture projectionist.

525
00:37:19,740 --> 00:37:22,034
Have you ever served on
a motion picture projectionist before?

526
00:37:22,117 --> 00:37:23,577
What?

527
00:37:23,660 --> 00:37:26,747
Uh, have you ever served
on ajury before?

528
00:37:57,778 --> 00:37:59,029
Hello, thing.

529
00:37:59,112 --> 00:38:00,739
Hello, at last.

530
00:38:01,990 --> 00:38:03,242
Well, well, well.

531
00:38:03,325 --> 00:38:05,035
Well, well, well, what?

532
00:38:06,245 --> 00:38:08,539
-Here we are.
-How true.

533
00:38:08,622 --> 00:38:10,082
Home at last.

534
00:38:10,123 --> 00:38:12,084
Took the words right out of my--

535
00:38:14,962 --> 00:38:16,213
Darling?

536
00:38:18,006 --> 00:38:20,467
Are you--are you all right?

537
00:38:20,551 --> 00:38:21,969
How do you mean?

538
00:38:22,052 --> 00:38:24,263
I mean in health and so forth.

539
00:38:24,304 --> 00:38:26,265
-Sure.
-Good.

540
00:38:27,349 --> 00:38:30,310
In health, excellent.
ln so forth, fair.

541
00:38:30,352 --> 00:38:32,312
-What's that some of?
-Some of daiquiris.

542
00:38:32,354 --> 00:38:33,605
Oh, good.

543
00:38:47,160 --> 00:38:50,706
Nobody died in the evening papers.
lsn't that nice?

544
00:38:50,789 --> 00:38:54,751
What do you suppose it is,
perverseness of human nature or what?

545
00:38:54,835 --> 00:39:00,048
It seems every night when Mary's out,
that's the night I want to stay home.

546
00:39:00,132 --> 00:39:03,177
Not me. I love to go out to dinner.
l'd rather go out than anything.

547
00:39:04,720 --> 00:39:07,431
-Where do you want to go tonight?
-No place. I want to stay home.

548
00:39:07,514 --> 00:39:09,349
Would you mind? Please?

549
00:39:09,433 --> 00:39:12,144
-Well, I don't know. All right.
-Cook up something ourselves.

550
00:39:12,227 --> 00:39:14,521
Something exotic. How would
you care for some of that?

551
00:39:14,605 --> 00:39:16,565
-Oh, I would.
-Of what?

552
00:39:16,648 --> 00:39:18,901
What you said.

553
00:39:18,984 --> 00:39:21,028
Fine. You gonna make it?

554
00:39:21,111 --> 00:39:23,530
You're not making too much sense.

555
00:39:24,281 --> 00:39:26,575
Do you want to talk to me
or read that paper?

556
00:39:26,658 --> 00:39:28,994
-Read the paper.
-Why?

557
00:39:29,036 --> 00:39:31,663
Quite a lot about me in it.
I guess that's why.

558
00:39:31,705 --> 00:39:32,998
Yes, l'll bet.

559
00:39:33,040 --> 00:39:35,000
You feel Pinky, cranky?

560
00:39:36,543 --> 00:39:38,462
You feel cranky, Pinky?

561
00:39:39,171 --> 00:39:40,672
Hard day, huh?

562
00:39:40,756 --> 00:39:42,883
-ln court all day?
-Yes.

563
00:39:42,966 --> 00:39:45,886
Had to mix it up
with a tough customer.

564
00:39:45,969 --> 00:39:48,472
-That always makes you irritable.
-Not so bad.

565
00:39:48,555 --> 00:39:51,642
-ln fact, it was a cinch.
-That's good, isn't it?

566
00:39:51,725 --> 00:39:55,062
-lsn't it?
-Oh, my, my, my.

567
00:39:55,145 --> 00:39:56,396
Dear?

568
00:39:58,440 --> 00:40:00,484
-You mean me?
-l sure do.

569
00:40:00,567 --> 00:40:02,528
-Listen.
-l'm all ears.

570
00:40:02,569 --> 00:40:04,571
-Oh, sure.
-What?

571
00:40:04,613 --> 00:40:06,657
You all right?

572
00:40:06,740 --> 00:40:09,701
Me? Sure. Of course. Why?

573
00:40:09,785 --> 00:40:13,455
I just wouldn't wanna think of you
not being all right, that's all.

574
00:40:16,583 --> 00:40:18,669
-You know what you are?
-What?

575
00:40:21,421 --> 00:40:24,049
-Lovable.
-l know.

576
00:40:24,132 --> 00:40:26,093
-Are you hungry?
-Yes, l'm starving.

577
00:40:27,427 --> 00:40:28,804
Let's go.

578
00:40:33,934 --> 00:40:36,436
Thank you, thank you,
from the bottom of my heart.

579
00:40:36,520 --> 00:40:38,522
Give you a real rubdown later
if you'll give me one.

580
00:40:41,066 --> 00:40:43,318
There. That's more like it.

581
00:40:43,402 --> 00:40:45,529
-Ouch!
-What's the matter?

582
00:40:56,665 --> 00:40:58,917
Anything for a hungry man?

583
00:41:00,002 --> 00:41:02,671
-Cheese. A soufflé, maybe?
-No, no.

584
00:41:02,754 --> 00:41:05,299
I've got enough on my mind
without a soufflé.

585
00:41:05,382 --> 00:41:07,301
There ought to be
some lamb left.

586
00:41:07,384 --> 00:41:10,095
I don't think--wait a minute.
Yes!

587
00:41:10,179 --> 00:41:11,805
-Lamb?
-Mm-hmm.

588
00:41:11,889 --> 00:41:14,308
-Lamb curry. What do you say?
-Perfect.

589
00:41:14,391 --> 00:41:15,642
With rice.

590
00:41:15,726 --> 00:41:18,228
-Chutney, chutney.
-Yes, I think so.

591
00:41:18,312 --> 00:41:20,606
Tea. Tea and curry.
That's the thing.

592
00:41:20,689 --> 00:41:23,609
-And salad.
-Give me the junk for the salad.

593
00:41:27,112 --> 00:41:30,949
Do you know, you were pretty cute
in there today, my little.

594
00:41:31,033 --> 00:41:33,785
You weren't so bad yourself, chum.

595
00:41:33,827 --> 00:41:36,496
-Do you mind a bit of garlic?
-Why a bit?

596
00:41:37,497 --> 00:41:40,250
-Pinkie?
-What, Pinky?

597
00:41:40,334 --> 00:41:42,961
-Do me a favor, will ya?
-Not too much salt?

598
00:41:43,003 --> 00:41:45,380
No. Drop the case.

599
00:41:45,464 --> 00:41:47,382
-l can't.
-Why not?

600
00:41:47,466 --> 00:41:49,635
-lt's my cause.
-l know.

601
00:41:49,676 --> 00:41:53,263
But I could see in there today,
it's gonna get sillier and messier...

602
00:41:53,347 --> 00:41:55,307
day by day by day.

603
00:41:55,390 --> 00:41:56,808
By day.

604
00:41:56,892 --> 00:41:59,478
-l don't ask many favors.
-Sure you do.

605
00:41:59,561 --> 00:42:02,189
-You can handle it from your desk.
-Not as good.

606
00:42:02,272 --> 00:42:05,484
Listen, darling, I know that
deep down you agree with me...

607
00:42:05,567 --> 00:42:08,362
with everything I want
and hope and believe in.

608
00:42:08,445 --> 00:42:11,490
We couldn't be so close if you didn't--
if I didn't feel that you did.

609
00:42:11,573 --> 00:42:13,325
-Oh, sure.
-Take this trial.

610
00:42:13,367 --> 00:42:16,078
Maybe it has some of the
inconvenience of the spotlight...

611
00:42:16,161 --> 00:42:17,955
but that's my whole point.

612
00:42:18,038 --> 00:42:20,249
Not any green peppers.
lndigestible.

613
00:42:20,332 --> 00:42:22,376
Everything's indigestible
to some people.

614
00:42:22,459 --> 00:42:24,378
Anyway, I don't like
green peppers.

615
00:42:24,461 --> 00:42:26,463
-No green peppers.
-Take the Boston Tea Party.

616
00:42:26,547 --> 00:42:29,132
-lnstead of the green peppers?
-What did they do?

617
00:42:29,216 --> 00:42:32,177
They dramatized an injustice.
That's all l'm trying to do.

618
00:42:32,261 --> 00:42:35,889
Yeah. People will be making jokes
about us over the radio before long.

619
00:42:35,973 --> 00:42:38,642
-All in a good cause.
-Your cause.

620
00:42:38,725 --> 00:42:40,018
Everybody's.

621
00:42:40,811 --> 00:42:43,480
Now--there's just enough for us.

622
00:42:56,118 --> 00:42:58,871
Hello, you well-known thing, you.

623
00:42:58,954 --> 00:43:00,289
How are you?

624
00:43:00,372 --> 00:43:03,584
You ask that because you can't
think of anything else to say.

625
00:43:03,667 --> 00:43:05,752
You don't care
whether I live or die.

626
00:43:07,546 --> 00:43:09,882
Hello, lawyer dear.
Seen all these?

627
00:43:09,923 --> 00:43:12,050
-Yeah. Thank you.
-Have some extras.

628
00:43:12,134 --> 00:43:14,887
Marvelous goings-on.
Everybody's talking about it.

629
00:43:14,928 --> 00:43:18,182
-Yeah. That's the idea.
-Sort of like the World Series.

630
00:43:18,265 --> 00:43:19,683
Yes, l'm afraid it is.

631
00:43:23,770 --> 00:43:27,399
What have you been eating,
raspberry jam or Amanda's face?

632
00:43:33,530 --> 00:43:34,990
Oh, very funny.

633
00:43:35,073 --> 00:43:37,534
-Very, very funny.
-l didn't even notice it.

634
00:43:37,618 --> 00:43:40,412
If you'd look at me once in a while,
you would notice things like that.

635
00:43:40,495 --> 00:43:42,748
Bicker, bicker. I give them
three months at the most.

636
00:43:42,831 --> 00:43:44,499
What do you want, anyway?

637
00:43:44,583 --> 00:43:46,585
As if you didn't know.

638
00:43:50,005 --> 00:43:52,007
-How's it coming?
-The show?

639
00:43:52,090 --> 00:43:54,051
Smashing. Simply smashing.

640
00:43:54,134 --> 00:43:57,304
Couldn't get much work done today.
Another notion got in the way.

641
00:43:57,387 --> 00:43:59,765
-A new song. Wanna hear it?
-Maybe some other time.

642
00:43:59,848 --> 00:44:02,684
It's not finished yet,
but please, it's for you.

643
00:44:02,768 --> 00:44:04,811
And, Adam, you don't have to listen.

644
00:44:08,315 --> 00:44:11,443
-He's written a song.
-Darling, don't be cross.

645
00:44:11,485 --> 00:44:13,237
He's sweet.

646
00:44:13,320 --> 00:44:14,571
Listening?

647
00:44:18,116 --> 00:44:23,163
Farewell, Amanda

648
00:44:23,247 --> 00:44:27,751
Adiós, addio, adieu

649
00:44:29,545 --> 00:44:34,174
Farewell, Amanda

